VALUES
(41, 11, 31, 40, 11, 7, 14, NULL, 'Connection through John the Baptist', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of John the Baptist as a prophet. In Mark, the questioning of Jesus'' authority relates to the acknowledgment of John''s prophetic role in Matthew. This connection highlights the importance of recognizing divine authority in prophetic figures.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 31, 40, 21, 25, 27, 'Why then did ye not believe him?', 'Authority of John the Baptist', 'Both passages emphasize the reasoning of the religious leaders regarding John''s authority. They grapple with the question of whether John''s baptism was from heaven or of men, leading to a similar conclusion about their disbelief in him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 31, 43, 1, 15, 15, NULL, 'Witness and Belief Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of witness and belief. In Mark, the questioning of belief relates to the acknowledgment of divine authority, while John highlights the witness of John the Baptist regarding Jesus'' preeminence, suggesting a call to recognize and believe in Him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 31, 43, 1, 36, 36, 'From heaven', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Authority', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus'' divine authority. In Mark, the questioning of Jesus'' origin reflects a struggle to acknowledge him, while in John, the declaration of Jesus as the ''Lamb of God'' affirms his heavenly identity.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 31, 43, 3, 29, 36, 'From heaven', 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of Jesus as coming from heaven. In Mark, the questioning of Jesus'' authority reflects the challenge to recognize divine truth, while John highlights that Jesus, as the one from above, speaks God''s words and testifies to divine reality.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 32, 40, 14, 5, 5, NULL, 'Fear of the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the people regarding John the Baptist''s prophetic status. This connection highlights how public perception influenced the actions of leaders in both accounts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 32, 40, 21, 46, 46, NULL, 'Fear of the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the people regarding the perception of prophets. In Mark, the fear is related to John being seen as a prophet, while in Matthew, the multitude views Jesus as a prophet, causing fear among the authorities.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 32, 41, 12, 12, 12, 'feared the people', 'Fear of the People', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the people, which influences the actions of the religious leaders. In Mark 11:32, they fear the people''s opinion of John the Baptist, while in Mark 12:12, they fear the people regarding Jesus'' parable.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 32, 41, 6, 20, 20, 'feared the people', 'Fear of John the Baptist', 'Both passages emphasize the fear that figures had regarding John. In Mark 11:32, the people feared to speak against him, while in Mark 6:20, Herod feared John for his righteousness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 32, 42, 7, 26, 29, 'that he was a prophet indeed', 'Connection of John the Baptist''s Prophetic Role', 'Both passages emphasize John the Baptist''s status as a prophet. Mark highlights the people''s recognition of John as a prophet, while Luke affirms his prophetic significance and greatness among those born of women.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 32, 42, 20, 6, 8, 'all men counted John, that he was a prophet indeed', 'Connection of Fear and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the people regarding John the Baptist''s prophetic status. This fear influences the leaders'' responses about Jesus'' authority, highlighting their concern for public opinion.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 32, 43, 10, 41, 41, 'that he was a prophet indeed', 'Connection Between John and Prophecy', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of John as a prophet. In Mark, the people viewed John as a true prophet, while in John, they acknowledge that John spoke truthfully about Jesus. This connection highlights the significance of John''s prophetic role in relation to Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 33, 23, 6, 9, 10, NULL, 'Understanding and Perception', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual blindness and lack of understanding. Both passages emphasize the inability to perceive truth, as seen in Jesus'' response and Isaiah''s message.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 33, 47, 4, 3, 4, NULL, 'Authority and Spiritual Blindness', 'This connection highlights the theme of hidden truths. In Mark, Jesus'' authority is questioned, and in 2 Corinthians, the gospel is hidden from those who do not believe, suggesting a spiritual blindness to divine authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 33, 53, 2, 10, 12, 'by what authority I do these things', 'Authority and Truth', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejecting truth and authority. In Mark, the leaders'' inability to recognize Jesus'' authority parallels the rejection of truth in 2 Thessalonians, leading to deception and condemnation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 33, 18, 5, 13, 13, 'We cannot tell', 'Wisdom and Authority Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of wisdom and authority. In Mark, Jesus challenges the authority of the wise, while Job speaks of God taking the wise in their own craftiness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 33, 20, 26, 4, 5, NULL, 'Foolish Responses and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of responding to folly. In Mark 11:33, Jesus refrains from answering the question posed by the religious leaders, paralleling Proverbs 26:4''s caution against engaging with fools. Both passages emphasize the wisdom in choosing when to respond.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 33, 23, 1, 3, 3, NULL, 'Understanding Authority and Recognition', 'This connection highlights the theme of recognition and understanding of authority. In Mark, the leaders fail to recognize Jesus'' authority, paralleling Isaiah''s depiction of Israel''s failure to know their owner.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 33, 24, 8, 7, 9, 'We cannot tell', 'Wisdom and Authority Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the failure to recognize divine authority and wisdom. In Mark, the leaders do not discern Jesus'' authority, while in Jeremiah, the people are criticized for not knowing the judgment of the Lord, despite claiming wisdom.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 1, 23, 5, 1, 4, 'a certain man planted a vineyard', 'Vineyard Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard that is carefully cultivated and expected to yield fruit. The imagery of planting, fencing, and building a tower is present in both texts, highlighting the care taken by the owner. This connection highlights the expectation of fruitful results from the vineyard.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 1, 41, 13, 34, 34, NULL, 'Parables of Stewardship and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of a master leaving his estate in the care of servants. Both passages emphasize the idea of a man taking a far journey and entrusting responsibilities to others.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 1, 22, 8, 11, 12, 'let it out to husbandmen', 'Vineyard Management Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard being let out to keepers or husbandmen. This connection highlights the responsibility of caretakers in managing the vineyard and the expectation of fruitfulness.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 1, 40, 25, 14, 14, 'into a far country', 'Parables of Stewardship', 'This connection highlights the theme of a man traveling into a far country, which appears in both passages. Both verses depict a scenario where individuals are entrusted with responsibilities while the master is away.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 1, 41, 4, 2, 2, 'by parables', 'Parables as Teaching Tools', 'Both passages emphasize the use of parables in teaching. Mark 12:1 introduces a specific parable about a vineyard, while Mark 4:2 notes that Jesus taught many things by parables.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 1, 45, 11, 17, 24, 'planted a vineyard', 'Vineyard and Olive Tree Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the cultivation and care of a vineyard or olive tree, representing God''s relationship with His people. The vineyard in Mark symbolizes Israel, while the olive tree in Romans illustrates the inclusion of Gentiles and the consequences of unbelief.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 1, 19, 80, 8, 16, 'planted a vineyard', 'Vineyard Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard, representing God''s care and cultivation. Mark 12:1 describes a man planting a vineyard, while Psalms 80:8-16 speaks of God bringing a vine out of Egypt and planting it.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 2, 43, 15, 1, 8, 'fruit of the vineyard', 'Connection of Vineyard Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of fruitfulness in relation to the vineyard. In Mark, the husbandmen are expected to yield fruit, while in John, the branches must abide in the vine to bear fruit.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 2, 7, 6, 8, 10, 'sent to the husbandmen a servant', 'Divine Sending of Servants', 'This connection highlights the theme of God sending messengers to His people. In Mark, a servant is sent to receive fruit, while in Judges, a prophet is sent to remind Israel of their obligations to God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 2, 12, 17, 13, 13, NULL, 'Servants and Prophets Connection', 'This connection highlights the role of servants sent by God to convey His messages. In Mark, the servant is sent to receive fruit, while in 2 Kings, prophets are sent to call Israel and Judah to repentance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 2, 14, 36, 15, 15, 'sent to the husbandmen a servant', 'Divine Sending of Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the act of sending servants or messengers by God to His people. This connection highlights God''s ongoing communication and care for those He has chosen.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
